1
00:00:05,606 --> 00:00:06,807
Previously on "ER."

2
00:00:06,840 --> 00:00:08,742
We do not need
a pediatric attending here.

3
00:00:08,775 --> 00:00:10,511
Don't worry.
It's not going to happen.

4
00:00:10,544 --> 00:00:12,312
Do you think I have what it
takes to be an attending?

5
00:00:12,345 --> 00:00:13,680
Of course, you do.

6
00:00:13,714 --> 00:00:16,182
‐ You've been a great friend.
‐ But?

7
00:00:16,216 --> 00:00:18,384
‐ But there's this other guy.
‐ Oh, yeah?

8
00:00:18,418 --> 00:00:20,286
We're both adults.

9
00:00:20,320 --> 00:00:22,623
'We enjoy each other.
Why not?'

10
00:00:24,290 --> 00:00:27,093
None of you wants the family
involved in your lives.

11
00:00:27,127 --> 00:00:28,529
He's not going
to break my heart.

12
00:00:28,562 --> 00:00:30,163
Men like him don't change.

13
00:00:30,196 --> 00:00:31,431
Let's start an epinephrine drip.

14
00:00:31,464 --> 00:00:32,699
Why don't we
also give her a heart

15
00:00:32,733 --> 00:00:34,100
transplant while we're at it?

16
00:00:35,101 --> 00:00:36,236
Peter.

17
00:00:46,279 --> 00:00:47,681
Aha.

18
00:00:47,714 --> 00:00:49,550
Sleeping beauty awakes.

19
00:00:49,583 --> 00:00:50,717
Hey.

20
00:00:50,751 --> 00:00:52,418
I was just checking
my messages.

21
00:00:52,452 --> 00:00:54,320
You didn't even stir
when the alarm went off.

22
00:00:54,354 --> 00:00:56,156
‐ Dead to the world.
‐ Ah.

23
00:00:56,189 --> 00:00:57,858
Well, you know...
it's not that often that

24
00:00:57,891 --> 00:00:59,292
I get the chance to sleep in.

25
00:00:59,325 --> 00:01:00,460
Yeah, yeah,
don't rub it in.

26
00:01:00,493 --> 00:01:02,428
Some of us have
to work Sundays.

27
00:01:02,462 --> 00:01:04,665
Oh, please.
You know I've had my share.

28
00:01:04,698 --> 00:01:06,466
Well, you're welcome to stay.

29
00:01:06,499 --> 00:01:08,869
No reason to waste
a warm bed.

30
00:01:08,902 --> 00:01:10,436
'No, no, no.'

31
00:01:10,470 --> 00:01:12,205
Actually, I need
to get going.

32
00:01:12,238 --> 00:01:13,707
There's tea and toast
in the kitchen.

33
00:01:13,740 --> 00:01:14,741
You'll have to boil the kettle

34
00:01:14,775 --> 00:01:17,310
but I think you can manage that.

35
00:01:17,343 --> 00:01:18,579
No.

36
00:01:18,612 --> 00:01:21,582
I've, uh, I've got
to go somewhere.

37
00:01:21,615 --> 00:01:24,851
Umh, not some other
clandestine meeting, I hope.

38
00:01:26,620 --> 00:01:28,722
Reese is getting baptized today.

39
00:01:28,755 --> 00:01:30,791
Protestant or Catholic?

40
00:01:30,824 --> 00:01:32,759
‐ Why?
‐ Just curious.

41
00:01:32,793 --> 00:01:34,795
AME.

42
00:01:34,828 --> 00:01:36,196
Look, I would have
invited you, but‐‐

43
00:01:36,229 --> 00:01:37,764
Ah, don't be silly.
It's a family thing.

44
00:01:37,798 --> 00:01:39,299
We've got time to go
home and change?

45
00:01:39,332 --> 00:01:40,767
‐ Yeah.
‐ Okay.

46
00:01:40,801 --> 00:01:42,569
Well, have
a good time then.

47
00:01:42,603 --> 00:01:44,771
Hey, and could you
lock the door on your way out?

48
00:01:44,805 --> 00:01:46,439
‐ Sure.
‐ Great.

49
00:01:49,510 --> 00:01:51,678
Hey, Peter.

50
00:01:51,712 --> 00:01:54,414
It was really lovely last night.

51
00:01:57,584 --> 00:01:59,620
‐ What are you doing?
‐ I'm hungry.

52
00:01:59,653 --> 00:02:01,855
‐ You can't start without her.
‐ Why not?

53
00:02:01,888 --> 00:02:03,824
I knew this brunch
was a bad idea.

54
00:02:03,857 --> 00:02:06,426
No. She's a little bit late.

55
00:02:06,459 --> 00:02:08,795
We should have met
on neutral territory.

56
00:02:08,829 --> 00:02:10,864
I told you, deep down..

57
00:02:10,897 --> 00:02:11,932
...your mother likes me.

58
00:02:11,965 --> 00:02:13,333
Keep dreaming.

59
00:02:13,366 --> 00:02:14,668
Finally.

60
00:02:14,701 --> 00:02:15,869
There you go.

61
00:02:19,339 --> 00:02:20,473
Hi.

62
00:02:20,507 --> 00:02:21,575
‐ Oh, Hello.
‐ Hello.

63
00:02:21,608 --> 00:02:23,677
What happened
to your front step?

64
00:02:23,710 --> 00:02:25,311
Oh..

65
00:02:25,345 --> 00:02:27,581
Did you get a flat tire or
something? Why are you late?

66
00:02:27,614 --> 00:02:29,182
Javier, this is
my daughter Carol.

67
00:02:29,215 --> 00:02:30,684
‐ Please to meet you.
‐ And her friend Doug.

68
00:02:30,717 --> 00:02:32,719
‐ How are you?
‐ Hey, nice to meet you.

69
00:02:32,753 --> 00:02:34,320
I'm sorry, we're late
but I couldn't get

70
00:02:34,354 --> 00:02:36,389
'your mother out of the house.'

71
00:02:36,422 --> 00:02:38,625
‐ Excuse me?
‐ Well, you know how she can be.

72
00:02:38,659 --> 00:02:40,226
Has to be perfect, right?

73
00:02:40,260 --> 00:02:41,795
‐ Allow me, sweet pea.
‐ No, I'll get this.

74
00:02:41,828 --> 00:02:43,396
Can I get you guys
something to drink?

75
00:02:43,429 --> 00:02:45,198
‐ Well, you have orange juice?
‐ Yes, we do.

76
00:02:45,231 --> 00:02:46,332
Two mimosas, please.

77
00:02:46,366 --> 00:02:47,934
‐ You brought champagne.
‐ Hm‐hmm.

78
00:02:47,968 --> 00:02:50,937
‐ Well, aren't we celebrating?
‐ Two happy couples right?

79
00:03:48,862 --> 00:03:50,931
'Did you see the way he kept
touching her back?'

80
00:03:50,964 --> 00:03:52,666
Ah, wasn't really paying
attention.

81
00:03:52,699 --> 00:03:54,701
Oh, you were too busy
laughing at his stupid jokes.

82
00:03:54,735 --> 00:03:56,036
He was funny.

83
00:03:56,069 --> 00:03:57,370
What was with "Sweet Pea."

84
00:03:57,403 --> 00:03:58,438
If he called her
one more time

85
00:03:58,471 --> 00:03:59,573
I was going to barf.

86
00:03:59,606 --> 00:04:00,774
I thought it was great.

87
00:04:00,807 --> 00:04:02,375
Doug, they met
at the racetrack.

88
00:04:02,408 --> 00:04:04,878
Now, that was
a senior citizen outing.

89
00:04:04,911 --> 00:04:07,013
So? They let anybody
in those groups.

90
00:04:07,047 --> 00:04:09,449
Alright. It's not true.

91
00:04:09,482 --> 00:04:10,851
All I know is that
this is the nicest

92
00:04:10,884 --> 00:04:11,885
your mother's
ever been to me.

93
00:04:11,918 --> 00:04:13,319
And I wanna keep it that way.

94
00:04:13,353 --> 00:04:14,354
You don't understand.

95
00:04:14,387 --> 00:04:15,589
My mother hates men.

96
00:04:15,622 --> 00:04:16,690
Hate's a strong word.

97
00:04:16,723 --> 00:04:18,424
Yeah, but in her case, accurate.

98
00:04:18,458 --> 00:04:20,961
‐ Maybe she's getting some.
‐ Oh, Doug, don't even go there.

99
00:04:20,994 --> 00:04:22,696
‐ How was it?
‐ Ugh, In like flint.

100
00:04:22,729 --> 00:04:23,730
'I'll get it.'

101
00:04:23,764 --> 00:04:24,998
You look like hell.

102
00:04:25,031 --> 00:04:26,533
Oh, you got to love
Saturday nights.

103
00:04:26,567 --> 00:04:27,968
ICU is packed.

104
00:04:28,001 --> 00:04:29,770
Two muggings, three bar fights.

105
00:04:29,803 --> 00:04:31,471
Four gangbanger drop‐offs

106
00:04:31,505 --> 00:04:34,307
and a bad stroganoff
from a wedding reception.

107
00:04:34,340 --> 00:04:35,742
Don't forget the guy
who licked the bottom

108
00:04:35,776 --> 00:04:37,010
of his girlfriend's shoe.

109
00:04:37,043 --> 00:04:38,945
‐ Why's that?
‐ She asked him to.

110
00:04:38,979 --> 00:04:40,514
Had to do a tongue culture.

111
00:04:40,547 --> 00:04:42,549
On that note, anybody hungry?

112
00:04:42,583 --> 00:04:44,951
No. Anna actually brought
Sunday doughnuts.

113
00:04:44,985 --> 00:04:47,320
Oh, so, cake isn't enough?
You have to deep fry it?

114
00:04:47,353 --> 00:04:48,822
That's the point.

115
00:04:48,855 --> 00:04:50,724
‐ How long are you on?
‐ 20 minutes.

116
00:04:50,757 --> 00:04:52,492
Medevac is incoming.

117
00:04:52,526 --> 00:04:54,528
29‐year‐old,
chemical accident.

118
00:04:54,561 --> 00:04:55,796
Bad chemical burn.

119
00:04:55,829 --> 00:04:57,731
Terrific.

120
00:04:57,764 --> 00:04:59,633
Hold the elevator.

121
00:04:59,666 --> 00:05:01,835
‐ Going down?
‐ Uh, up, actually.

122
00:05:01,868 --> 00:05:03,003
Well, up's fine.

123
00:05:04,437 --> 00:05:06,339
Surprised to see you
here on a Sunday.

124
00:05:06,372 --> 00:05:08,474
Ah, well, I'm just
full of surprises.

125
00:05:08,509 --> 00:05:10,544
‐ Covering the ER?
‐ Mm‐hmm.

126
00:05:10,577 --> 00:05:12,679
I've noticed you signed up for a
lot of extra coverage lately.

127
00:05:12,713 --> 00:05:13,980
Well, you know, idle hands.

128
00:05:14,014 --> 00:05:15,381
Yeah,
I know exactly what you mean.

129
00:05:15,415 --> 00:05:16,717
In fact, Lizzy,
I think it's about time

130
00:05:16,750 --> 00:05:19,052
you and I had
a little sit‐down.

131
00:05:19,085 --> 00:05:20,954
‐ Is there a problem?
‐ No. No problem.

132
00:05:20,987 --> 00:05:22,388
Let me buy you lunch.

133
00:05:22,422 --> 00:05:23,824
Is it about
the hemoAid study?

134
00:05:23,857 --> 00:05:26,426
That and the future.

135
00:05:26,459 --> 00:05:27,994
‐ Alright.
‐ Good.

136
00:05:28,028 --> 00:05:30,797
‐ Then, in about an hour?
‐ Mm‐hmm.

137
00:05:36,737 --> 00:05:39,439
‐ You said hydrofluoric acid?
‐ Yeah.

138
00:05:39,472 --> 00:05:41,642
‐ Not hydrochloric?
‐ I don't think so.

139
00:05:41,675 --> 00:05:42,909
‐ Why?
‐ Well some‐‐

140
00:05:42,943 --> 00:05:44,778
I heard we had a fire victim.

141
00:05:44,811 --> 00:05:46,079
Actually, chemical burn.

142
00:05:46,112 --> 00:05:47,548
How bad?

143
00:05:47,581 --> 00:05:48,982
‐ What do you got?
‐ 'Paul Canterna.'

144
00:05:49,015 --> 00:05:50,651
'31‐year‐old security guard.'

145
00:05:50,684 --> 00:05:52,152
Second and third‐degree
chemical burns

146
00:05:52,185 --> 00:05:54,588
to the trunk, right arm
and and both legs.

147
00:05:54,621 --> 00:05:55,956
Doused with hydrofluoric acid.

148
00:05:55,989 --> 00:05:57,624
‐ What happened?
‐ It was stupid.

149
00:05:57,658 --> 00:05:59,793
The vat was leaking.
I tried to tightened the valve.

150
00:05:59,826 --> 00:06:01,628
Alright, sir,
just lie back and relax.

151
00:06:01,662 --> 00:06:03,530
I got in the shower
to rinse it off.

152
00:06:03,564 --> 00:06:06,399
Gave him five of morphine,
two liters normal saline.

153
00:06:06,432 --> 00:06:07,801
You feeling
any more pain now?

154
00:06:07,834 --> 00:06:09,169
‐ It's okay now.
‐ Alright, let's go.

155
00:06:09,202 --> 00:06:10,537
Let's move him.

156
00:06:20,747 --> 00:06:21,748
‐ Morning.
‐ Hey.

157
00:06:24,217 --> 00:06:25,819
Usually, significant
improvement occurs

158
00:06:25,852 --> 00:06:27,187
within the first three months.

159
00:06:27,220 --> 00:06:29,022
Oh, he's still working
on his motor skills.

160
00:06:29,055 --> 00:06:31,558
The fact is, Chase's progress
has slowed considerably.

161
00:06:31,592 --> 00:06:33,927
That's all the more reason
for aggressive therapy.

162
00:06:33,960 --> 00:06:35,696
He can get that at home.

163
00:06:35,729 --> 00:06:38,599
Look, I just want what's
medically best for my cousin.

164
00:06:38,632 --> 00:06:40,701
Gamma, I think
this is a big mistake.

165
00:06:40,734 --> 00:06:43,770
John, it's often wise
to listen to the perspective

166
00:06:43,804 --> 00:06:46,172
of those
not personally involved.

167
00:06:46,206 --> 00:06:47,941
'Chase is getting worse.'

168
00:06:47,974 --> 00:06:50,877
He's lost nearly all function
on his left side.

169
00:06:50,911 --> 00:06:52,779
No, he just favors his right.

170
00:06:52,813 --> 00:06:54,648
You have to force him
to use his left.

171
00:06:54,681 --> 00:06:57,117
I wish it were that simple.

172
00:06:57,150 --> 00:06:59,052
It is. Watch.

173
00:06:59,085 --> 00:07:01,154
John, please.

174
00:07:01,187 --> 00:07:02,523
Hey, Chase.

175
00:07:03,957 --> 00:07:05,491
How you doing?

176
00:07:05,526 --> 00:07:06,560
How you doing?

177
00:07:06,593 --> 00:07:09,630
You, uh, you want to draw?

178
00:07:09,663 --> 00:07:11,898
He was left‐handed.
He was drawing just last week.

179
00:07:11,932 --> 00:07:13,534
You want to draw
something for me?

180
00:07:13,567 --> 00:07:14,901
John, this isn't necessary.

181
00:07:14,935 --> 00:07:16,102
Hmm? Okay?

182
00:07:17,203 --> 00:07:19,205
‐ Okay?
‐ Okay.

183
00:07:19,239 --> 00:07:21,508
'Okay. Why don't you go ahead
and you take the pencil?'

184
00:07:21,542 --> 00:07:22,676
No, no, no.

185
00:07:23,644 --> 00:07:25,512
Other hand.

186
00:07:27,548 --> 00:07:28,582
Come on.

187
00:07:28,615 --> 00:07:30,150
He can do this.

188
00:07:30,183 --> 00:07:32,052
'It's okay. It's okay.'

189
00:07:32,085 --> 00:07:34,521
There you go.
And you're all set.

190
00:07:34,555 --> 00:07:37,658
What do you want
to draw, huh?

191
00:07:37,691 --> 00:07:38,825
‐ You.
‐ Me?

192
00:07:38,859 --> 00:07:40,794
You want to draw me?
Okay, go ahead.

193
00:07:42,295 --> 00:07:43,630
I rushed him.

194
00:07:45,165 --> 00:07:47,000
I rushed him.
You can't, you can't rush him.

195
00:07:47,033 --> 00:07:48,268
Alright?

196
00:07:48,301 --> 00:07:50,837
Here we go.
Let's try again.

197
00:07:50,871 --> 00:07:52,038
Yeah.

198
00:07:53,740 --> 00:07:56,510
Needs calcium chloride,
ten percent solution.

199
00:07:56,543 --> 00:07:58,178
‐ Start with five Amps.
‐ Five Amps?

200
00:07:58,211 --> 00:08:01,915
Yeah. And set up an infusion.
One gram every 15 minutes.

201
00:08:01,948 --> 00:08:04,885
So, Mr. Canterna,
feeling any more pain?

202
00:08:04,918 --> 00:08:06,920
It's starting to get numb,
doctor. Is that bad?

203
00:08:06,953 --> 00:08:09,289
Our immediate concern is with
the fluoride in the acid.

204
00:08:09,322 --> 00:08:12,158
‐ Well, like‐like toothpaste?
‐ Not exactly.

205
00:08:12,192 --> 00:08:15,529
The uh, calcium, uh, can be
drawn out of your cells.

206
00:08:15,562 --> 00:08:16,930
So, what does that mean?

207
00:08:16,963 --> 00:08:20,133
Well, it depends how much has
penetrated your skin.

208
00:08:20,166 --> 00:08:22,569
Right now, we're giving you
calcium intravenously

209
00:08:22,603 --> 00:08:24,705
to counteract the effect.

210
00:08:24,738 --> 00:08:26,607
Is there any family
you'd like us to call?

211
00:08:26,640 --> 00:08:28,174
Is there something
you're not telling me, doctor?

212
00:08:28,208 --> 00:08:30,076
Hydrofluoric burns
can be serious.

213
00:08:30,110 --> 00:08:33,246
So, is there any family you'd
like us to call in the area?

214
00:08:33,279 --> 00:08:35,616
Nah, I don't really have
family in Chicago.

215
00:08:35,649 --> 00:08:37,150
Okay. I'll, I'll be right back.

216
00:08:37,183 --> 00:08:40,921
Carol, uh, can, uh,
you keep an eye on him?

217
00:08:40,954 --> 00:08:42,222
Make sure he's comfortable.

218
00:08:42,255 --> 00:08:43,256
‐ And watch his heart rate.
‐ Alright.

219
00:08:43,289 --> 00:08:44,691
Tell me
if his leg gets worse.

220
00:08:44,725 --> 00:08:47,160
It's not his leg
I'm worried about.

221
00:08:50,831 --> 00:08:52,165
‐ Hey.
‐ Hey.

222
00:08:52,198 --> 00:08:54,134
You look nice.

223
00:08:54,167 --> 00:08:56,136
Thanks. Hey, is,
uh, Carla here yet?

224
00:08:56,169 --> 00:08:57,237
‐ Inside.
‐ Oh.

225
00:08:57,270 --> 00:08:59,205
‐ Hey, Uncle Peter.
‐ Hey.

226
00:08:59,239 --> 00:09:00,974
Where is she?

227
00:09:01,007 --> 00:09:02,008
Who?

228
00:09:02,042 --> 00:09:03,076
Your girlfriend.

229
00:09:03,109 --> 00:09:04,210
‐ Steven.
‐ What?

230
00:09:04,244 --> 00:09:06,747
You said
he had a new girlfriend.

231
00:09:06,780 --> 00:09:08,615
Well, I don't.

232
00:09:08,649 --> 00:09:10,717
Well, dad said he heard grandma
turning over in her grave.

233
00:09:10,751 --> 00:09:12,218
Alright. That's enough.

234
00:09:12,252 --> 00:09:13,920
Both of you go in there
and get a seat.

235
00:09:17,123 --> 00:09:18,324
'Peter.'

236
00:09:18,358 --> 00:09:21,595
Oh, come on.

237
00:09:21,628 --> 00:09:22,796
You remember Roger?

238
00:09:22,829 --> 00:09:24,230
How you doing, man?

239
00:09:24,264 --> 00:09:26,166
Uh, hey, hey.

240
00:09:26,199 --> 00:09:28,268
Uh, Carla, can I talk
to you for a minute?

241
00:09:28,301 --> 00:09:29,936
‐ All set?
‐ Yes.

242
00:09:29,970 --> 00:09:31,204
Uh, we should do
a little rehearsal

243
00:09:31,237 --> 00:09:32,973
before everyone arrives.

244
00:09:33,006 --> 00:09:34,808
Um, um, mom and dad..

245
00:09:34,841 --> 00:09:36,309
Uh, um, I'm‐I'm the father.

246
00:09:36,342 --> 00:09:38,745
Oh, I'm sorry.

247
00:09:38,779 --> 00:09:40,380
‐ Uh, who's holding the baby?
‐ I am.

248
00:09:40,413 --> 00:09:42,849
Okay. Now, l‐listen if you'd
just step back here.

249
00:09:42,883 --> 00:09:44,350
Yeah, come on, everybody.

250
00:09:44,384 --> 00:09:46,186
Just kind of move around
and make way here, please.

251
00:09:46,219 --> 00:09:48,021
Thank you.
No, no, over here.

252
00:09:50,423 --> 00:09:53,026
That's good.
That's good.

253
00:09:53,059 --> 00:09:55,161
Here you go, little pickle.

254
00:09:55,195 --> 00:09:56,362
Yeah, mom in the middle.

255
00:09:56,396 --> 00:09:59,032
Dad, dad, right here
on the end.

256
00:09:59,065 --> 00:10:00,366
Right here.
Just move back.

257
00:10:00,400 --> 00:10:02,302
Thank you. Okay.

258
00:10:02,335 --> 00:10:04,370
'You know, I wasn't even
supposed to go into work today.'

259
00:10:04,404 --> 00:10:07,340
I was home
restoring my car and..

260
00:10:07,373 --> 00:10:09,643
...the weekend guy
called in sick.

261
00:10:09,676 --> 00:10:11,845
So, I figured I could use
the overtime, you know?

262
00:10:11,878 --> 00:10:13,046
What kind of car do you have?

263
00:10:13,079 --> 00:10:14,915
It's a '63 'vette.

264
00:10:14,948 --> 00:10:18,151
She's an eyesore,
but she's got matching numbers.

265
00:10:18,184 --> 00:10:20,220
I'm going to fix her up.
She's gonna be worth..

266
00:10:22,422 --> 00:10:24,324
It's hurting under my skin.

267
00:10:24,357 --> 00:10:25,992
I'm going to give you
something more for the pain.

268
00:10:28,294 --> 00:10:30,196
How long is this going
to hang me up for?

269
00:10:30,230 --> 00:10:31,197
It's hard to say.

270
00:10:36,036 --> 00:10:38,071
He's already severely
hypocalcemic

271
00:10:38,104 --> 00:10:39,305
and the leg is necrotic.

272
00:10:39,339 --> 00:10:40,807
Any EKG changes?

273
00:10:40,841 --> 00:10:42,175
Prolonged QT.

274
00:10:42,208 --> 00:10:43,677
He's at risk
for an arrhythmia.

275
00:10:43,710 --> 00:10:45,411
What does toxicology say?

276
00:10:45,445 --> 00:10:48,148
Hydrofluoric burns of this
magnitude are always fatal.

277
00:10:48,181 --> 00:10:49,883
There's no new treatment.

278
00:10:49,916 --> 00:10:51,251
His family on the way?

279
00:10:51,284 --> 00:10:53,386
‐ He doesn't have any in town.
‐ Hm.

280
00:10:53,419 --> 00:10:55,188
You might have time
to fly somebody in.

281
00:10:55,221 --> 00:10:57,357
Yep.

282
00:10:57,390 --> 00:10:59,826
‐ Guess I better go tell him.
‐ Mm‐hmm.

283
00:11:03,096 --> 00:11:04,865
This is really starting
to hurt, doctor.

284
00:11:04,898 --> 00:11:06,199
We can do something
about that.

285
00:11:06,232 --> 00:11:07,433
I'll give him
another five of morphine.

286
00:11:07,467 --> 00:11:10,103
You okay? You don't look
so good yourself.

287
00:11:10,136 --> 00:11:12,472
Mr. Canterna, the calcium
we're giving you

288
00:11:12,506 --> 00:11:16,142
can't reverse the chemical
reaction in your body.

289
00:11:16,176 --> 00:11:18,912
W‐what do you mean,
"Chemical reaction"?

290
00:11:18,945 --> 00:11:22,315
The fluoride is binding
to your cellular calcium..

291
00:11:22,348 --> 00:11:24,785
...to form calcium fluoride.

292
00:11:24,818 --> 00:11:27,821
A crystal salt that seeps
into your body tissues.

293
00:11:27,854 --> 00:11:29,756
So‐so, what does that mean?

294
00:11:29,790 --> 00:11:32,726
We're already starting to see
changes in your cardiogram.

295
00:11:32,759 --> 00:11:34,294
So, now, what?

296
00:11:34,327 --> 00:11:37,263
As the calcium level
in your cardiac cells falls..

297
00:11:38,965 --> 00:11:43,269
...your heart's going
to begin to fail.

298
00:11:43,303 --> 00:11:46,807
What? Are you telling me
that I'm going to die?

299
00:11:46,840 --> 00:11:48,041
We're doing everything we can.

300
00:11:48,074 --> 00:11:49,209
Is that a yes?

301
00:11:52,178 --> 00:11:54,047
Yes.

302
00:11:54,080 --> 00:11:55,148
How‐how long?

303
00:11:58,084 --> 00:11:59,219
Days?

304
00:12:00,887 --> 00:12:01,822
Maybe 12 hours.

305
00:12:09,963 --> 00:12:11,932
Is there anybody you'd like us
to call, Mr. Canterna?

306
00:12:20,240 --> 00:12:21,975
Mr. Canterna?

307
00:12:27,548 --> 00:12:29,883
I don't feel that bad.

308
00:12:29,916 --> 00:12:31,852
Well, you let me know
if the pain increases.

309
00:12:31,885 --> 00:12:34,555
It hurts. I just don't feel
like I'm dying or anything.

310
00:12:34,588 --> 00:12:36,056
We're gonna do
everything we can

311
00:12:36,089 --> 00:12:38,124
to keep you as comfortable
as possible.

312
00:12:38,158 --> 00:12:39,526
Maybe he's got it wrong.

313
00:12:39,560 --> 00:12:42,462
Shouldn't you call
a specialist or something?

314
00:12:42,495 --> 00:12:44,330
I feel like you guys
are giving up on me..

315
00:12:44,364 --> 00:12:46,399
We're not giving up
on you, Mr. Canterna.

316
00:12:46,432 --> 00:12:48,134
I promise you that.

317
00:12:48,168 --> 00:12:50,003
We're gonna do
everything we can.

318
00:12:50,036 --> 00:12:52,806
You sure there isn't someone
we can call for you?

319
00:12:52,839 --> 00:12:53,940
It's too late.

320
00:12:53,974 --> 00:12:55,308
Why? How far away are they?

321
00:12:55,341 --> 00:12:58,211
No, I been gone too long.
She won't come.

322
00:12:58,244 --> 00:12:59,379
Who won't?

323
00:13:00,413 --> 00:13:02,315
My daughter.

324
00:13:02,348 --> 00:13:04,084
21 years old.
Complains of neck, back..

325
00:13:04,117 --> 00:13:05,986
Hold up. we're full here.
Next room.

326
00:13:06,019 --> 00:13:07,487
Neck, back and bilateral
ankle pain

327
00:13:07,521 --> 00:13:09,389
following a 75‐foot fall
into the river.

328
00:13:09,422 --> 00:13:11,424
‐ From where?
‐ The Train Bridge.

329
00:13:11,457 --> 00:13:13,560
Sinus rhythm:
A and O times three.

330
00:13:13,594 --> 00:13:16,930
ETOH on breath.
Sensory and motor exam normal.

331
00:13:16,963 --> 00:13:20,266
Okay, CBC, dip a urine cross
table c‐spine

332
00:13:20,300 --> 00:13:21,902
chest and pelvic x rays.

333
00:13:21,935 --> 00:13:23,103
‐ Does that hurt?
‐ A little.

334
00:13:23,136 --> 00:13:24,270
Okay, and lift.

335
00:13:25,572 --> 00:13:26,940
What were you doing
on the bridge?

336
00:13:26,973 --> 00:13:29,075
It's a long story.

337
00:13:29,109 --> 00:13:30,611
‐ How about here?
‐ No.

338
00:13:30,644 --> 00:13:32,045
BP is 120/70.

339
00:13:32,078 --> 00:13:34,848
‐ Pulse is 112.
‐ Is that bad?

340
00:13:34,881 --> 00:13:36,950
No. We're just gonna check
to make sure you're okay.

341
00:13:36,983 --> 00:13:37,984
Good peripheral pulse.

342
00:13:38,018 --> 00:13:39,352
Normal cap refill.

343
00:13:39,385 --> 00:13:41,154
Follow with bilateral
ankle films

344
00:13:41,187 --> 00:13:42,488
and, uh, call psych.

345
00:13:42,523 --> 00:13:44,390
Psych?
Wait, I don't need a shrink.

346
00:13:44,424 --> 00:13:45,926
Relax. Everything's fine.

347
00:13:45,959 --> 00:13:47,260
I didn't jump,
if that's what you think.

348
00:13:47,293 --> 00:13:48,629
‐ Okay.
‐ No, I'm serious.

349
00:13:48,662 --> 00:13:49,896
‐ I didn't jump.
‐ Okay.

350
00:13:49,930 --> 00:13:51,532
‐ Take any drugs?
‐ No.

351
00:13:51,565 --> 00:13:53,934
I‐I was there with my buddies.
We were just fooling around.

352
00:13:53,967 --> 00:13:55,135
How much have you had to drink?

353
00:13:55,168 --> 00:13:56,503
A couple beers.

354
00:13:56,537 --> 00:13:59,172
Well, you also have a couple
of broken ankles.

355
00:13:59,205 --> 00:14:00,907
‐ Throw in a BA.
‐ Where are you going?

356
00:14:00,941 --> 00:14:02,375
We're gonna take care of
everything. Just relax.

357
00:14:02,408 --> 00:14:03,544
Is everything okay in there?

358
00:14:03,577 --> 00:14:05,445
Joker jumps off a bridge
and walks away

359
00:14:05,478 --> 00:14:06,947
with a couple of ankle
fractures.

360
00:14:06,980 --> 00:14:08,114
‐ So to speak.
‐ Yeah. Called psych?

361
00:14:08,148 --> 00:14:09,415
‐ Yeah.
‐ I'll tell Weaver.

362
00:14:09,449 --> 00:14:10,483
‐ Surgical consult?
‐ Uh, Trauma two.

363
00:14:10,517 --> 00:14:11,518
Straight ahead.

364
00:14:11,552 --> 00:14:12,953
Mark, he changed his mind.

365
00:14:12,986 --> 00:14:14,387
He really wants
to see his daughter.

366
00:14:14,420 --> 00:14:16,122
Oh, I thought he didn't have
family in town.

367
00:14:16,156 --> 00:14:18,258
No, he does. He just hasn't seen
her in six years.

368
00:14:18,291 --> 00:14:20,326
‐ How old is she?
‐ Six and a half.

369
00:14:20,360 --> 00:14:21,461
‐ Oh, boy.
‐ Don't worry.

370
00:14:21,494 --> 00:14:22,629
‐ I'll take care of it.
‐ You sure?

371
00:14:22,663 --> 00:14:24,297
Yeah, yeah. You go home.
Get some rest.

372
00:14:24,330 --> 00:14:25,566
No no no. Listen I should
probably stick around.

373
00:14:25,599 --> 00:14:27,133
Mark, there's nothing
else for you to do

374
00:14:27,167 --> 00:14:28,669
except hold his hand,
which is my job.

375
00:14:28,702 --> 00:14:30,470
‐ Go on. Get out of here.
‐ Alright. Thank you.

376
00:14:30,504 --> 00:14:32,338
'And another breath in.'

377
00:14:32,372 --> 00:14:35,275
‐ Got a sec?
‐ Sure. I'll be right back.

378
00:14:35,308 --> 00:14:38,545
CBC, pulse ox, lytes,
ABG and a chest film.

379
00:14:38,579 --> 00:14:40,914
Still waiting
for an ICU bed.

380
00:14:40,947 --> 00:14:43,550
Pulse ox is
falling slowly.

381
00:14:43,584 --> 00:14:45,519
Uh, I didn't talk to him
about a vent yet.

382
00:14:45,552 --> 00:14:47,420
I wanted to let
the news set in and..

383
00:14:47,453 --> 00:14:49,322
...Carol is looking
for the family.

384
00:14:49,355 --> 00:14:52,526
‐ Alright. Have a good Sunday.
‐ Thank you.

385
00:14:52,559 --> 00:14:54,528
‐ Sorry about that.
‐ No. I know you're busy.

386
00:14:54,561 --> 00:14:57,497
I don't usually come to the
emergency room...for the flu.

387
00:14:57,531 --> 00:14:59,365
But I can't seem
to beat this cough.

388
00:14:59,399 --> 00:15:01,234
Hmm. How long you been
feeling fatigued?

389
00:15:01,267 --> 00:15:03,570
‐ A‐about a month.
‐ Any weight loss?

390
00:15:03,604 --> 00:15:06,472
Mmm. I've been so stressed
planning this wedding.

391
00:15:06,507 --> 00:15:08,208
Oh! Congratulations.

392
00:15:08,241 --> 00:15:10,511
Is that a daughter
or a granddaughter?

393
00:15:10,544 --> 00:15:12,478
Why, it's my wedding.

394
00:15:12,513 --> 00:15:14,414
After four years
I told her it was about

395
00:15:14,447 --> 00:15:15,582
time to make a commitment.

396
00:15:15,616 --> 00:15:17,183
Well, good for you.

397
00:15:17,217 --> 00:15:19,019
Gives me less than
a month to get better.

398
00:15:19,052 --> 00:15:20,353
No promises.

399
00:15:20,386 --> 00:15:22,155
‐ You might have pneumonia.
‐ Pneumonia?

400
00:15:22,188 --> 00:15:24,257
We'll know more once
we get a chest X‐ray.

401
00:15:24,290 --> 00:15:26,693
Hey, Anna, are you the one who
had that voodoo woman yesterday?

402
00:15:26,727 --> 00:15:28,962
‐ Oh, She's back?
‐ Yeah. Exam three.

403
00:15:28,995 --> 00:15:31,097
Chief complaint, "Voodoo man
has taken over her body."

404
00:15:31,131 --> 00:15:32,232
Wait a minute,
this isn't the same one.

405
00:15:32,265 --> 00:15:33,600
My voodoo patient
was 60‐something.

406
00:15:33,634 --> 00:15:35,235
I had a voodoo guy last week.

407
00:15:35,268 --> 00:15:36,503
Oh, no.
Voodoo epidemic.

408
00:15:36,537 --> 00:15:38,271
Sorry.

409
00:15:38,304 --> 00:15:41,474
Yeah? Ma'am, your ex‐husband
is in critical condition.

410
00:15:41,508 --> 00:15:43,009
I know you are at work.

411
00:15:43,043 --> 00:15:44,711
He just..

412
00:15:44,745 --> 00:15:46,713
Look, he's going to die tonight.

413
00:15:46,747 --> 00:15:48,515
He just wants to see Molli.

414
00:15:48,549 --> 00:15:50,517
‐ Anybody home?
‐ What have you got?

415
00:15:50,551 --> 00:15:52,018
Pedestrian versus auto.

416
00:15:52,052 --> 00:15:54,020
Head contusion, brief LOC.

417
00:15:54,054 --> 00:15:55,421
Broken arm,
vitals are stable.

418
00:15:55,455 --> 00:15:58,391
‐ What's open, Chuny?
‐ Uh, curtain three.

419
00:15:58,424 --> 00:15:59,626
Curtain three?

420
00:15:59,660 --> 00:16:01,094
‐ Cerebral palsy?
‐ I don't know.

421
00:16:01,127 --> 00:16:02,462
Somebody clipped
his wheelchair.

422
00:16:02,495 --> 00:16:03,630
He couldn't tell us
if he was hurt or not.

423
00:16:03,664 --> 00:16:04,765
No one was with him?

424
00:16:04,798 --> 00:16:06,767
Nope. Just found him
on the street.

425
00:16:06,800 --> 00:16:08,502
Okay. Sir, can you
tell me your name?

426
00:16:08,535 --> 00:16:09,603
No it's not use.

427
00:16:09,636 --> 00:16:10,737
You can't understand him.

428
00:16:10,771 --> 00:16:12,372
He might have
the uh, a subdural

429
00:16:12,405 --> 00:16:13,740
that could impair his speech.

430
00:16:13,774 --> 00:16:15,175
We should get a head CT.

431
00:16:15,208 --> 00:16:16,610
How do you do a neuro exam?

432
00:16:16,643 --> 00:16:19,279
It would help if we
knew his baseline.

433
00:16:19,312 --> 00:16:20,614
Okay.

434
00:16:20,647 --> 00:16:25,018
Sir, can you, can you push in
against my hand?

435
00:16:25,051 --> 00:16:27,087
Alright, let's start
with a c‐spine.

436
00:16:27,120 --> 00:16:28,121
Carter, have you seen Elizabeth?

437
00:16:28,154 --> 00:16:29,455
No.

438
00:16:29,489 --> 00:16:30,557
Wasn't she called down
for a consult?

439
00:16:30,591 --> 00:16:31,758
‐ I just got here.
‐ Anna?

440
00:16:31,792 --> 00:16:33,594
O‐oh, she's right there,
actually.

441
00:16:35,295 --> 00:16:36,462
‐ Hey.
‐ Peter.

442
00:16:36,496 --> 00:16:37,664
I thought you
weren't coming in.

443
00:16:37,698 --> 00:16:39,566
Uh, I wasn't,
but I decided to come in

444
00:16:39,600 --> 00:16:41,267
and do some,
uh, post‐op notes.

445
00:16:41,301 --> 00:16:42,569
You look dapper.

446
00:16:42,603 --> 00:16:44,204
‐ Thank you.
‐ How was the baptism?

447
00:16:44,237 --> 00:16:46,540
‐ Good. It was good.
‐ Nothing afterwards?

448
00:16:46,573 --> 00:16:48,141
Hey listen, you want
to get something to eat?

449
00:16:48,174 --> 00:16:50,143
Oh, I wish. I've got
this thing with Romano.

450
00:16:50,176 --> 00:16:51,678
‐ What thing?
‐ Lunch.

451
00:16:51,712 --> 00:16:53,279
I think it's got something to do
with my fellowship renewal.

452
00:16:53,313 --> 00:16:54,615
Ah.

453
00:16:54,648 --> 00:16:56,082
Did you really come in
for post‐op notes?

454
00:16:56,116 --> 00:16:57,651
Yeah, yeah.
So, I'll see you later?

455
00:16:57,684 --> 00:16:59,085
Oh, yeah. I hope so.

456
00:16:59,119 --> 00:17:00,453
'You should call the military.'

457
00:17:00,486 --> 00:17:02,756
They might have
an antidote or something.

458
00:17:02,789 --> 00:17:05,291
A buddy of mine
says they use stuff like this.

459
00:17:05,325 --> 00:17:07,594
Yeah, it's not really
the same thing.

460
00:17:07,628 --> 00:17:09,062
I just want you to know.

461
00:17:09,095 --> 00:17:10,230
I know.

462
00:17:11,197 --> 00:17:12,398
Did you find her?

463
00:17:12,432 --> 00:17:14,434
Uh, I talked
to your ex‐wife.

464
00:17:14,467 --> 00:17:15,836
What'd she say?

465
00:17:15,869 --> 00:17:19,072
She said that she's
sorry, but, um..

466
00:17:19,105 --> 00:17:21,307
She's not going to bring Molli?

467
00:17:21,341 --> 00:17:23,143
No.

468
00:17:23,176 --> 00:17:24,711
She, um, she knows
what's happening to me?

469
00:17:27,581 --> 00:17:29,683
That's okay.

470
00:17:29,716 --> 00:17:31,618
Hey, it's for
the best, I guess.

471
00:17:31,652 --> 00:17:33,587
I'm sorry.

472
00:17:33,620 --> 00:17:36,289
I was going to make it
up to her, but..

473
00:17:36,322 --> 00:17:39,359
I guess I ran out
of time, you know?

474
00:17:39,392 --> 00:17:41,194
At some point,
you'll have to let us know

475
00:17:41,227 --> 00:17:43,664
if you want to be put
on a ventilator.

476
00:17:43,697 --> 00:17:45,098
Dr. Weaver,
do you have a minute?

477
00:17:45,131 --> 00:17:46,867
Yeah. Uh, what is it?

478
00:17:46,900 --> 00:17:49,335
Auto versus pedestrian,
possible head injury.

479
00:17:49,369 --> 00:17:51,271
‐ What's the problem?
‐ Cerebral palsy.

480
00:17:51,304 --> 00:17:53,674
He's, uh, tough to assess
and we don't want to hurt him.

481
00:17:53,707 --> 00:17:57,210
Alright. Call me
at the first sign of arrhythmia.

482
00:17:57,243 --> 00:17:59,279
Are you sure it's CP?
He might be posturing.

483
00:17:59,312 --> 00:18:00,313
No, he's conscious.

484
00:18:00,346 --> 00:18:01,548
Well, is he on any meds?

485
00:18:01,582 --> 00:18:02,749
I don't know.
He has no family.

486
00:18:02,783 --> 00:18:04,184
We can't understand
a word he's saying.

487
00:18:04,217 --> 00:18:05,218
‐ Did you check‐‐
‐ Wait, hang on.

488
00:18:05,251 --> 00:18:06,252
Let me grab this one quick.

489
00:18:06,286 --> 00:18:08,221
Yo! I need a portable c‐spine.

490
00:18:08,254 --> 00:18:10,223
‐ Oh, X ray, trauma two.
‐ No, Maggie. I got him.

491
00:18:10,256 --> 00:18:11,658
‐ When did you call?
‐ I didn't.

492
00:18:11,692 --> 00:18:13,326
‐ But I need to clear a neck.
‐ So do I.

493
00:18:13,359 --> 00:18:15,295
‐ Well, how bad is yours?
‐ How bad is yours?

494
00:18:15,328 --> 00:18:16,530
'Hey, I need a hand here!'

495
00:18:16,563 --> 00:18:18,231
Carter, grab that gurney.
Is he breathing?

496
00:18:18,264 --> 00:18:20,200
Yeah. I need a C‐collar
and backboard. Let's move.

497
00:18:20,233 --> 00:18:22,202
‐ I got it.
‐ Connie, get Doug.

498
00:18:22,235 --> 00:18:24,437
‐ Why didn't you call 911?
‐ I thought I'd get here faster.

499
00:18:24,470 --> 00:18:25,772
How long has he been
unconscious?

500
00:18:25,806 --> 00:18:27,473
Uh, he was awake in the car.
He just stop crying.

501
00:18:27,508 --> 00:18:29,309
‐ Pulse is weak and thready.
‐ What happened?

502
00:18:29,342 --> 00:18:30,911
Uh, I had him for the weekend.
We were washing the car.

503
00:18:30,944 --> 00:18:32,378
‐ 'I didn't see him.'
‐ We need the room now.

